The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, April 17, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, April 16: The rate of inflation fell marginally to 4.40 per cent for the week ended April 3 despite a whopping 20 per cent rise in vegetable prices and a substantial hike in the prices of fruits, milk and fuels for industries. The point-to-point wholesale price index (WPI) inflation fell by 0.07 per cent in the first week of this financial year from the previous weeks level of 4.47 per cent. It was as high as 6.66 per cent in the year-ago period. WPI was up by 0.3 per cent to 180.5 points mainly due to a rise in the prices of primary items like fruits, vegetables and fuels.																								 New Delhi, April 16: The settlement process between the warring industrialists, Rahul Bajaj and his brother Shishir, seems to have hit a roadblock, as they are yet to agree on how much money should go in different hands. It has got stuck on one or more matters. We are working on it, said Madhur Bajaj.																								 New Delhi, April 16: Maruti Udyog Ltd is talking to several global automakers, including Peugeot, to make diesel engines locally, said MD Jagdish Khattar.																								 Mumbai, April 16: Benefiting from higher revenue collection and prudent expenditure management, the governments fiscal deficit for 2003-04 is expected to be lower than the estimated 4.8 per cent, while the economy will grow over 8 per cent in 2004-5 and beyond, said finance minister Jaswant Singh.																								 New Delhi, April 16: Foreign venture capital worth $1.5-2 billion and another Rs 10,000 crore from Sidbis SSI fund are expected to bolster small companies in the country this year. About $1.5-2 billion are expected to be invested by private equity funds this year, said Ajay Relan, chief of Citigroup venture capital India.																								 New Delhi, April 16: The government today said it has chalked out a contingency plan for tackling coal shortages at power stations and hoped to tide over the crisis by May end.																								 Mumbai, April 16: The National Stock Exchange will hold a three-hour trading session tomorrow from 11 am. There would be a trading on BSE as well.
